 accepted -- tSupporting ‘experts by experience’ – a champion idea -- tEngaging communities – sharing the learning -- tThe engagement industry – some personal reflections -- tOverview: Colliding worlds – the journey towards collaborative governance -- tHow can information technology work for well-being? Data, dialogues and digital media -- tRecords help us make sense of our lives -- tRecords access and empowered patients, 2017 -- tLearning to build a high-quality information system to support high-quality renal care -- tEmbracing social technology -- tEnlightening the next user -- tPatients’ stories – digital gifts that can change the world -- tTemptations of cheap data -- tOverview: Innovation in cultures, feelings and roles -- tWhat kind of learning, what kind of leadership? -- tManagers and leadership, now and then -- tHarnessing a Hydra – managing to change the NHS -- t“Ask the patient what they want” -- tThe heart and art of leadership -- tHealth leadership for the 21st century – a new, holistic, co-productive endeavour -- tForty years of innovation in community responses to the needs of people with learning difficulties -- tFrom hard to reach to within reach – the ‘how’ of community engagement in the era of the Big Society -- tDisciplined conversation, facilitated dialogue, measured progress -- tLeadership as if people matter – the Innovative Headteachers Programme -- tOverview: What kind of leadership? -- tBetter health in harder times – towards a sustainable NHS -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor years the NHS has been the most trusted of public institutions and the envy of many around the world. But today there is turmoil. Painful shortcomings in clinical care and patient experience, together with funding cuts, threaten to dig deep into service levels and standards. Seventy years of technically advanced medicine provided free to the population has produced a widespread perception of patients as passive consumers of health care. This book explores how we may renew for our times the collective compact that created our public services in the 1940s. Voices from service users and service providers show how this can be done. They offer testimony of what goes wrong and what can be put right when working together becomes the norm. Sections explore new ways of living and working with long-term conditions, more meaningful and effective approaches to service redesign, use of information technology, leadership, co-production and creating and accounting for quality. Accessible to a wide range of readers, with short, accessible contributions, this is a book to provoke and inspire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPublic healthxCitizen participation. 0aPublic health. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aAnsell, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBacon, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, Laurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarle, Nan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Rohhss, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraft, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Georgina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunningham, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Celia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Celia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/voca